    <text>
        <body>
            <div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1935-06-12T13:00:00-05:00"
                frus:doc-dateTime-min="1935-06-12T13:00:00-05:00" n="184"
                subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d184">
                <note rend="inline" type="source">793.94/7027a: Telegram</note>
                <head>
                    <hi rend="italic">The <gloss type="from">Acting Secretary of State</gloss> to
                        the Second Secretary of Legation in China</hi> (<persName type="to">
                        <hi rend="italic">Atcheson</hi>
                    </persName>), <hi rend="italic">at Nanking</hi>
                </head>
                <opener>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">Washington</hi>
                        </placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1935-06-12T14:00:00-04:00"
                            >June 12, 1935—2 p.m.</date>
                    </dateline>
                </opener>
                <p>46. Associated Press report from Nanking under date line June 12 states that
                    Central Political Council, meeting in urgent session closed to the press and to
                    the public, was reported today to have rejected the Japanese demands affecting
                    North China; that Chinese reports of the meeting stated that the Council had
                    telegraphed Ho Ying-chin instructing <pb facs="0344" n="232" xml:id="pg_232"/>
                    him to “prepare for eventualities should the Japanese carry out threats to
                    advance upon Peiping and Tientsin.”</p>
                <p>Please investigate accuracy of report and send reply as soon as practicable.</p>
                <closer>
                    <signed>
                        <hi rend="smallcaps">Phillips</hi>
                    </signed>
                </closer>
            </div>
        </body>
    </text>
